		   <table class="mform"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%" >
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Mon, Mar 14th 8:52 PM2005 </span><span class="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=1110468099644988581&num=36&page=0&post=1&replyto=1110851514601058579"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1110851514601058579></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id="Sage">gbaji</span></a><b><span id="Sage"><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><span style="font-size:9px;color: red;">There is no 5th star.</span><br />10533 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.03]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%">
<p><blockquote><b class="sm">Friar Reinman wrote:</b><hr size="1" />So when you are talking about &quot;swings&quot;, you are encompassing double/triple attacks, and bash/kick into a single swing.&nbsp;&nbsp;I think that is why people refer to it as a round.  You being a tank should have noticed, especially on slowed mobs that the damage comes in, for lack of a better word, &quot;rounds&quot;.  Is that a fair enough explanation?<hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br /> <br />It's still a misrepresentation. A &quot;round&quot; implies a specific time period (ie: mobX gets 3 attacks per round). No such thing exists in EQ. The rate at which each mob swings is different. So a &quot;round&quot; of swings from one mob might occur every 3 seconds, for another it might be 5 seconds, for yet another it might be every second. Then, when slowed, the rate of those swings decreases by the amount of the slow. <br /> <br />I'm just pointing out that it's incredibly misleading to talk of stopping &quot;rounds&quot; of attacks as though a &quot;round&quot; is some quantifiable quality. It's not. <br /> <br />Additionally, with regards to stuns, they don't actually prevent the attacks, they just delay them. Something that is critical to the difference between a &quot;round&quot; and just having delays on your swings. If there were actual combat rounds and I stun you for a round, you just lose your attacks that round. Next round, you start out as normal. But stuns don't prevent the delay cycle from continuing, they just prevent the swing from happening until the stun ends. The instant the stun stops, all the swings that are &quot;waiting&quot; occur simultaneously. It's one of the reasons why you'll see a paladin tank and take no damage for 10 seconds, and then get pummeled into the dust in the next 4 or 5 (which can throw off clerics who aren't aware that just because I'm not taking damage right now does *not* mean they can expect that rate of damage to continue). <br /> <br />Why is this different? If we had actual rounds, then we'd have a time period in a round when you'd attack. let's say that a round consists of 4 seconds (just to make things cleaner). Let's also say that your weapons have a &quot;delay&quot; that determines when they go off during that round. So a fast weapon might go off 1 second into the round, and a slower one would go off 3 seconds into the round. Double and tripple attacks would be managed somehow (either go off right then, or spaced out over the rest of the round after your delay has been reached). That's how round based game systems work. It's totally different then the delay based system that EQ uses. <br /> <br />The key difference is in an ability like stun. In a round based combat system, that 4 second stun would simply stun the mob for a round. So if his attacks normally went off 3 seconds into a 4 second round (delay 3), he'd just lose his attacks for the round he's stunned and start the next round over. In effect, that stun stopped him from attacking for 7 seconds since the first 4 (full round) he's stunned, and then he starts over on round 2, attacking 3 seconds into that around. With a delay based system, that doesn't happen. He'd normally attack 3 seconds after the start of combat. But because he's stunned for 4 seconds, his attack is delayed until immediately after 4 seconds ends. Then 3 seconds later he'd attack again. The point being that in a round based combat system, after 8 seconds (two rounds), the stunned mob would have gotten *one* swing 3 seconds into the second round. In a delay based system, by 8 seconds into the game, the exact same stunned mob would attack on second 4, then again on second 7, and be 1 second into his next swing on second 8. Note, that that's actually only put him one second behind what he would have been anyway if he'd not been stuned at all (non-stunned mob would have attacked on 3, then 6, then been 2 seconds into his third swing by second 8. <br /> <br />Technically, I'm ignoring something anyway. Delays accrue after swings, so the mob actually would get a swing on second 0, then 3, then 6. A stunned mob would actually be reduced significantly for that first 4 seconds assuming that the paladin drops his stun perfectly just before the mob would have started swinging (that's an artform btw!). In practice, you only recieve a significant dps reduction from mobs if you can chain 2 or more stun spells together to effectively &quot;slow&quot; the mobs overall rate of swings. Which is why this can be a problem. There are level ranges where you will only have *one* stun spell that works on the mobs you are fighting. For example, from level 66 to 68, a paladin will only have *one* 4 second stun that he can use for mobs his level (and up to 2 levels lower!). That's clearly a significant power reduction from when he was able to chain stun up to 5 stuns against mobs his level or lower back in his mid 50s. <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /><blockquote><b class="sm">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />A 4 second stun mitigates/avoids proportionate amounts of  damage at level 65 then it does at level 10 and therefore it scales with content.  A 50 hp DD only really &quot;fits&quot; into one level range in the game and therefore does not scale with content.  I hope you can see the difference.<hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br /> <br />Of course I see the difference. But that's not what was compared. Someone compared snares to stuns, and implied that pally stuns somehow became *more powerful* while a snare did not. No one was talking about DD spells. <br /> <br />I never argued that a stun doesn't scale proportionately to the mobs you are stunning. Of course it does. 4 seconds of stun is relatively equal in value to 4 seconds of stun regardless of level of the mob. But can you not also see that a snare is of the same value on a level 70 mob as it is on a level 1 mob as well? And can we not also agree that a 75% slow is of just as much value on a level 70 mob as it is on a level 1 mob? Those are all &quot;proportional&quot; spells. They have an absolute effect on the mob they are cast on. <br /> <br />My issue is that there was an implication that paladin stuns got more powerful in relation to the mobs, and that's absolutely not true. The snaring ability of a ranger is just as relatively effective at level 70 as it was at level 55. The slowing ability of a shaman or chanter is just as relatively effective at level 70 as it was at level 55. But the stunning ability of a paladin is much less at level 70 then it was at level 55. It is proportionally less effective exactly because the more stuns a paladin can affect a given mob with, the greater the total effect his stuns will have. A shaman only needs to get one slow to land, and he's done. The mob's damage is reduced by X percent. A ranger only need to get one snare to land and he's done. The mobs movement is reduced by X percent. A paladin much continually chain stuns to significantly reduce the damage output of the mob. By reducing the number of stuns he's got that can affect the mobs he's hunting from 5 to 1 or 2, that significantly reduces the effectiveness of his stun spells. I'm not talking about how effective a single 4 second stun is. I'm talking about the fact that at level 55, that stun was a 6 seconds stun, and he had 5 of them. At level 66, he's got *one* 4 second stun that will affect mobs his level or higher. That's an absolutely *huge* reduction in power.</p>
